# Spring for GraphQL

## Schema-First Approach
Define schema in `src/main/resources/graphql/`:
```graphql
# schema.graphqls
type Query {
    orderById(id: ID!): Order
    orders(page: Int = 0, size: Int = 20): OrderConnection!
}

type Mutation {
    createOrder(input: CreateOrderInput!): Order!
}

type Order {
    id: ID!
    description: String!
    total: BigDecimal!
    status: OrderStatus!
    items: [OrderItem!]!
    customer: Customer!
}

input CreateOrderInput {
    items: [OrderItemInput!]!
    shippingAddress: AddressInput!
}

enum OrderStatus {
    PENDING, CONFIRMED, SHIPPED, DELIVERED, CANCELLED
}
```

## Controller Mappings
```java
@Controller
public class OrderGraphQlController {
    private final OrderService orderService;

    @QueryMapping
    public Order orderById(@Argument Long id) {
        return orderService.findById(id)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new OrderNotFoundException(id));
    }

    @QueryMapping
    public Connection<Order> orders(@Argument int page, @Argument int size) {
        return orderService.findAll(PageRequest.of(page, size));
    }

    @MutationMapping
    public Order createOrder(@Argument CreateOrderInput input) {
        return orderService.create(input);
    }
}
```

## N+1 Prevention with DataLoader / @BatchMapping
```java
@Controller
public class OrderGraphQlController {

    @BatchMapping
    public Map<Order, Customer> customer(List<Order> orders) {
        var customerIds = orders.stream().map(Order::customerId).toList();
        var customers = customerService.findByIds(customerIds);
        return orders.stream().collect(Collectors.toMap(
            order -> order,
            order -> customers.get(order.customerId())
        ));
    }

    @BatchMapping
    public Map<Order, List<OrderItem>> items(List<Order> orders) {
        var orderIds = orders.stream().map(Order::id).toList();
        var itemsByOrder = itemService.findByOrderIds(orderIds);
        return orders.stream().collect(Collectors.toMap(
            order -> order,
            order -> itemsByOrder.getOrDefault(order.id(), List.of())
        ));
    }
}
```
**ALWAYS** use `@BatchMapping` for relationship fields to prevent N+1 queries.

## Security
```java
@Controller
public class AdminGraphQlController {

    @QueryMapping
    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
    public List<User> allUsers() {
        return userService.findAll();
    }

    @MutationMapping
    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('USER') and @orderSecurity.isOwner(#input.orderId, authentication)")
    public Order cancelOrder(@Argument CancelOrderInput input) {
        return orderService.cancel(input);
    }
}
```

## Error Handling
```java
@ControllerAdvice
public class GraphQlExceptionHandler {

    @GraphQlExceptionHandler
    public GraphQLError handleNotFound(OrderNotFoundException ex) {
        return GraphQLError.newError()
            .errorType(ErrorType.NOT_FOUND)
            .message(ex.getMessage())
            .build();
    }

    @GraphQlExceptionHandler
    public GraphQLError handleValidation(ConstraintViolationException ex) {
        return GraphQLError.newError()
            .errorType(ErrorType.BAD_REQUEST)
            .message("Validation failed")
            .extensions(Map.of("violations", ex.getConstraintViolations().stream()
                .map(v -> Map.of("field", v.getPropertyPath().toString(), "message", v.getMessage()))
                .toList()))
            .build();
    }
}
```

## Testing with GraphQlTester
```java
@GraphQlTest(OrderGraphQlController.class)
class OrderGraphQlControllerTest {
    @Autowired
    private GraphQlTester graphQlTester;

    @MockBean
    private OrderService orderService;

    @Test
    void shouldReturnOrder() {
        given(orderService.findById(1L)).willReturn(Optional.of(testOrder()));

        graphQlTester.documentName("orderById")
            .variable("id", 1)
            .execute()
            .path("orderById.description").entity(String.class).isEqualTo("Test Order")
            .path("orderById.status").entity(String.class).isEqualTo("CONFIRMED");
    }
}
```

## GraphQL vs REST Decision Guide
| Factor | Prefer GraphQL | Prefer REST |
|--------|---------------|-------------|
| Clients with varying data needs | Yes (mobile vs web) | Fixed contract is fine |
| Deep nested relationships | Yes (single query) | Multiple round trips |
| File upload / download | REST is simpler | Yes |
| Caching | Complex (no HTTP caching) | Simple (HTTP cache headers) |
| Team familiarity | GraphQL expertise present | REST is well-known |
| Ecosystem tooling | Growing | Mature |

## Configuration
```yaml
spring:
  graphql:
    graphiql:
      enabled: true  # dev only
    schema:
      printer:
        enabled: true  # dev only
```
Disable `graphiql` and schema printer in production.
